metadata.name: Balanced #60
Vertical World #106
metadata.description:
This artwork is a kind of my inquiry about ambiguous boundaries.
I was a child who liked to draw but always been dissatisfied with my work. Now through coding, I was able to create the "feelings" that I wanted to express. This work is not to imitate a certain landscape or painting style, but simply paint with different brushes, and cooperate with the randomness of the computer.
"I" creates horizontal order, and "computer" creates vertical disorder. My intention is to create
ambiguous visuals in a way that doesn't give specific images, but vague atmosphere.
The meaning is computer-generated and positioned through your eyes.
(It may take more time to render if you using Firefox browser.)

- Press [s] to save png image

Created by haxenfan using p5js.

metadata.name: Magic Mushrooms #49
metadata.description:
Magic Mushrooms is an algorithm that generates 1990‚Äôs style random dot autostereogram drawings of psychedelic fungus.  I am not going to attempt to tell you how to see the mushrooms in these drawings.  Instead, you should watch a youtube video about stereograms or get very high with someone who was around in the 90s.

All due props and attribution go to the authors of the open source library stereogram.js, a modified version of which was used in this project to draw a bunch of colored squares in a grid that can trick the brains of some human beings into seeing magic mushrooms.  Like stereogram.js, this project is in no way affiliated with Magic Eye Inc.

Created by @capnganj - one love <3

metadata.name: Aurora At Mount St. Matrice #33
metadata.description:
At the gateway of waking and sleep, warmed by a molten heart; into the arms of night - be bathed by her falling hair.

Process: Forged in Hydra.

üåê A note on rarity and variety: 

Although there are many variations possible within this piece, they are on the subtler side.

As this is a highly temporal piece, these variations ask you to dive into the experience of the piece in order to fully appreciate them. Please proceed bearing this in mind.

Experiment with the aspect ratio of this piece using the ‚Äòopen live‚Äô function below the viewport - it can be enjoyed elastically [as with my previous works here]. A larger frame provides for a deeper experience.

As with a handful of my works, an instance of .blend() is used in this piece, and does cause some slight thinning and dimming to the preview capture. Once more, this still preview is to be considered a skeletal scan of a moment within this piece.

objkt.name: M'Fing Dots on a M'Fing Grid #78

metadata.name: M'Fing Dots on a M'Fing Grid #78
metadata.description:
M'Fing Dots on a M'Fing Grid was an fxhash speedrun any% < 720 minutes project. Started at 10:30am Fri 5th August 2022, and finished at 10:30pm Fri 5th August 2022.

The repo for the code base can be found at: https://github.com/revdancatt/mfing-dots-on-a-mfing-grid - progress of writing code over the 12 hours can be seen in the commit history.

## THE PROJECT

The idea behind the project was to take one of the simplest things in generative art, randomly coloured dots on a grid.

Many projects use dots on a grid as the base foundation for building more complexity. However, just the dots themselves are often considered too simple to have as a project on their own.

Given the limited amount of time for a 12-hour speed run, I decided to see if I could take something as simple as dots and inject just a little bit of GenArt personality into it. Adding textures, variations and controlled colour selection.

It's about as simple you can get with dots on a grid, without being simple. This is my [speed run] version, show me yours.

## SPEED RUN

The tradition of doing a "speed run" on fxhash was started by Alexis Andr√© (@MacTuitui) and his "fxhash SpeedRun: any% < 960 minutes" project (#11995), described as "A performance piece. From cloning the template to a decent piece in less than 960 minutes".

Two more speed run collections have been created "Consequence Broadcast" (#13359) and "Beacon" (#17542) both by Amy Goodchild.

This is a fxhash speedrun any% < 720 run.

The any% is from game speed running and means "to get to the end with any % finished", meaning you don't have to 100% complete the game, just get to the end credits. For a gen art project it means you can use libraries and copy bits and bobs from your previous code, without having to do everything from scratch.

< 720 means that it's done in less than 720 minutes, in this case 12 hours.

metadata.name: EYES #76
metadata.description:
The beauty and soul of eyes have always fascinated me. There are billions of eyes in the world, all with different colors, textures and shapes and each one is still unique. With this project, I wanted to capture that natural beauty of the eyes, but also give them my unique colorful style.

Zombie and Cat eyes are more rare. Who will collect the Zombie Cat eye?

----

Created with the help of amazing cables.gl. For optimization purposes, in order to make the project load properly on fxhash, I had to use 2 textures for the eye pupil shapes instead of procedurally generating them. There is also hdr map loaded for the reflections.  

Press E to download the generated image.

----

All who collected NEBULAE were added to the reserve list. <3

metadata.name: Lucky Oracles #704
metadata.description:
"Lucky Oracles" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

Eko33, is a Swiss-French generative artist who has been at the forefront of digital arts since 1999 when he started writing code to create generative artworks and installations. He made his debut using a Commodore SX-64 and floppy disks. Since then, his work has been exhibited in Museums, International art fairs, and biennales. His work is focused on nonfigurative, generative art while using custom algorithms and innovative technology.

Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/ Official Twitter account: https://twitter.com/eko3316 Official Instagram account: https://www.instagram.com/eko33studio/ https://linktr.ee/eko33 "I create deterministic generative art based on crypto hash seeds. Maximizing algorithmic diversity."

If you want to receive an e-mail alert when I release new artwork subscribe here => https://eko33.com/email-alerts
